<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="283" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1478,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,318,1614,1637]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Type material:</emphasis>
Holotype ♂, Bulgaria, Strandzha Mts, Kondolovo Village, 
<date box="[950,1060,1614,1637]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" value="2004-06-30">30.6.2004</date>
, leg. M. Langouov. Paratypes: 1 ♂, same data as holotype; 4 ♂, same locality, 4.08.1998; 1 ♂, same locality, 
<date box="[939,1049,1645,1669]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" value="1998-09-10">9.10.1998</date>
; 1 ♂, same locality, 
<date box="[1268,1377,1645,1669]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" value="1998-07-11">7.11.1998</date>
; 1 ♂, same locality, 
<date box="[304,425,1677,1701]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" value="2000-11-11">11.11.2000</date>
; 1 ♂, Gramatikovo village, 
<date box="[722,844,1677,1701]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" value="1999-11-13">13.11.1999</date>
; 1 ♂, same locality, 8.2000, leg. V. Popov. Other material (
<bibRefCitation author="Demircan" box="[375,826,1710,1733]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" refString="Demircan, N. &amp; Topcu, A. (2015) A contribution to the spider fauna of the European part of Turkey (Araneae). Serket, 14 (4), 176 - 183." type="journal article" year="2015">Demircan &amp; Topcu 2015, not examined</bibRefCitation>
): 4 ♂, 6 ♀, Turkey, Kırklareli Province, Vize District, Balkaya Village, Uzuntarla (Domuzdere) Cave (Demirkan &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Topcu" box="[821,961,1742,1765]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" refString="Demircan, N. &amp; Topcu, A. (2015) A contribution to the spider fauna of the European part of Turkey (Araneae). Serket, 14 (4), 176 - 183." type="journal article" year="2015">Topçu, 2015</bibRefCitation>
). The material is not examined because the images presented by Demirkan &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Topcu" box="[515,648,1774,1797]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" refString="Demircan, N. &amp; Topcu, A. (2015) A contribution to the spider fauna of the European part of Turkey (Araneae). Serket, 14 (4), 176 - 183." type="journal article" year="2015">Topçu, 2015</bibRefCitation>
where sufficient to match their specimens with the males described here. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,330,1806,1829]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Etymology:</emphasis>
From the Latin words ‘brevis’ (short) and ‘embolus’.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="283" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1478,2021]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,318,1838,1861]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The new species has somatic characters (notched trochanters, patellae with dorsal spines only, male palps with patellar apopyse) that correspond well to those of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dimitrov &amp; Deltshev &amp; Lazarov" authorityYear="2017" box="[932,1043,1870,1893]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Histopona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1043,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Histopona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, according to 
<bibRefCitation box="[1201,1432,1870,1893]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" refString="Bolzern, A., Pantini, P. &amp; Isaia, M. (2013) Revision of the Histopona italica group (Araneae: Agelenidae), with the description of two new species. Zootaxa, 3640 (1), 23 - 40. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3640.1.2" type="journal article">
Bolzern 
<emphasis box="[1294,1350,1870,1893]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">et al.</emphasis>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
. The male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Dimitrov &amp; Deltshev &amp; Lazarov, 2017" authorityName="Dimitrov &amp; Deltshev &amp; Lazarov" authorityYear="2017" box="[293,539,1902,1925]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Histopona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviemboli" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[293,539,1902,1925]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Histopona breviemboli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[548,608,1902,1925]" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily separated from all the other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dimitrov &amp; Deltshev &amp; Lazarov" authorityYear="2017" box="[1079,1190,1902,1925]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Histopona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1079,1190,1902,1925]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Histopona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the overall shape of the male bulbus, the short embolus and its position, the thorn-like radix, the shape of the patellar apophysis and the simple (with no branches) and pointed at the end tibial apophysis of the pedipalp (
<figureCitation box="[1079,1176,1966,1989]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1813,1835]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,194,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,194,1793]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Histopona breviemboli sp. n., male holotype. 1. Habitus, dorsal view; 2. Habitus, ventral view; 3 – 5. Male palp, prolateral, ventral and retrolateral view. Scale lines: 2.0 — 1, 2; 0.2 — 3 – 5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847460/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">Figs 3–5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1188,1232,1966,1989]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1149,1171]" captionTargetBox="[170,1421,203,1114]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1128]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Histopona breviemboli sp. n., male paratype. 6 – 8. Male palp, prolateral, ventral and retrolateral view. Scale lines: 0.2." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847462/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="283">6–8</figureCitation>
). It’s not related to any of the known species.
</paragraph>
